@unnumbered Check downloads: recovery, deletion, shutdown, reboot ...

Downloads can be controlled in different ways depending on the type of operation to be performed.
Starting from the terminal allows the operations listed in the command presentation to be executed: @ref {The ZDL command}. Since ZDL can be closed without interrupting downloads, this control mode can be adopted at any time, once execution has started. For @emph {close without interrupting downloads}:
@itemize @minus
@item
if started in standard mode, type @kbd {M-q} (@kbd {<Alt> + <q>} keys)
@item
from interactive mode, type @kbd {Q} (@kbd {<Shift> + <q>} keys)
@end itemize

Once @emph {closed} (or even @emph {killed} interrupting downloads), ZDL can be restarted using new options.

@unnumberedsubsec An example, starting from a practical problem: add options to downloads started by the browser.
@table @emph
@item Problem:
I want to download files from Easybytez using @emph {Flashgot}, but I want to
also use the options @option {- login}, @option {- max-downloads =} and @option {- clean}, which are not
set by default. How can I use these additional features
using the browser (with @emph {Flashgot}), if these can be activated
only from the terminal?

@item Solution:
@itemize @minus
@item
start zdl in a terminal, from the destination directory,
    using all the options I need:
    @command {zdl -m --login --clean}
@item
using @emph {Firefox}, I click with the right mouse button on the links of
    download file and start the download with @emph {Flashgot}: download
    it is not carried out immediately and the links are registered by zdl for
    be processed by another active instance of the program (that one
    in the terminal)
@item
when I finished recording the links, I go back to the terminal and, without
    write anything, type @kbd {M-x}
@end itemize
@end table

@ * @ *
@unnumberedsubsec Manual control of downloads.
ZDL processes the registered @emph {links}, generating for each a temporary file from which it can extract information about the file to be downloaded and the download in progress, intact or completed. Thanks to this information, it is possible to control the download processes, either automatically by ZDL, or manually by the user.

ZDL downloads can be controlled manually through the interactive mode, which can be activated from the standard one by entering @kbd {Mi} (@kbd {<Alt> + <i>} keys) or from any @emph {Bash} terminal from the same download directory, using the @option {-i | --interactive} option. If there is no start-up instance and automatic management of downloads, from the interactive interface it is possible to start the @emph {demon} mode, which acts in the background as @emph {server} and is independent of the startup terminal. To manage the downloads and the closing of ZDL in daemon mode, it is still necessary to use the interactive interface, which acts as @emph {client}. @ *
The commands are listed in the same interactive interface: it is possible to modify the maximum number of downloads (from 1 to 9, by typing the number keys, or unlimited, by typing the key @kbd {m}), the type of downloader to use (Axel o Wget, by typing @emph {a} or @emph {w}), start the default editor to edit the list of links to be processed (@emph {e} key), select with @emph {s} the downloads in management for @emph {restart them} (ZDL interrupts the current download and processes the next one until the end of the registered list, then restarts from the first and so on), @emph {terminate} them definitively without deleting the files downloaded so far or @ emph {eliminate them} completely. For these last three operations it is possible to select several downloads at a time, indicating the identification numbers separating them with spaces.

@unnumberedsubsec Manual control of downloads still to be processed.
In the absence of temporary files related to @emph {link} not yet processed, it is possible to intervene manually using an @emph {editor} (@ref {Editor}).

@htmlend

